        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "My Bosch dishwasher shows E15 — what do I do?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "E15 is the anti-flood float switch triggered — water has entered the base pan underneath the dishwasher. Safety system shut down the machine to prevent water damage. First: shut off the water supply valve under the sink or behind the dishwasher (there should be a shut-off for the dishwasher inlet line). Some owners try the 'Tilt Fix' — tilt the dishwasher backward to drain the base pan, error clears temporarily. This is not a repair — it means the root leak is still there and will retrigger within days or weeks. Real fix: identify the leak source (inlet valve slow drip, door gasket, circulation pump seal, Aquastop hose internal leak), repair or replace failed component, then drain the pan. Float switch itself rarely fails — part 00611316 on 300/500/800 series, 12019637 on newer Benchmark/800+ units. $185-$265 float switch replacement + the underlying leak repair."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "E22, E24, and E25 — what's the difference?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "All three are drainage-related but point to different components. E22 means the fine filter is blocked and water can't drain from the sump — clean the filter (bottom of dishwasher cavity, under the spray arm), 80% resolve free with cleaning. E24 means drainage fault at the intermediate stage — drain hose kinked, drain pump cover loose (underneath filter), or garbage disposal connection plug not removed. E25 means drain pump blockage at the pump nozzle or impeller — debris (glass shards, plastic fragments) jammed the pump. Order of diagnostic: clean filter first (free, fixes E22 and often E24), check pump cover seating (free, resolves some E24), inspect drain hose for kinks, then inspect pump impeller (requires partial disassembly, $245-$385 pump replacement if damaged)."
        }
